column2: A simple but effective Data Flow architecture, HanishKVC, 1990-1997, PartB

column4: Set the dependency list of each register, as well as the expression to calculate its value.
Each register has a dependecy list associated with it, which tells what registers it depends on.
Read value from read registers in its dependency list, write value into its write register and update its own global dirty bit
ie At beginning of each execute cycle, check each registers" depedency list against the global register dirty list
if ANDing of both lists results in a non zero set, then that register requires to be updated, by recalculating its value.
Copy the new value if any in write register into corresponding read register.
Ensure that the global dirty/updated bit corresponding to each updated register is set.

column3: Each register is maintained as two copies/registers internally

column4: Any register which depends on this register, will use the read copy for its calculation to update its value
If a register is being updated by doing its associated calculation, the resulting value will be written to its write copy.
At the end of each execute cycle the new value in write register gets copied to read register, as well as the global dirty/updated bit for that register will be set.

column3: A neural network could be implemented using such a architecture.
'Auto updating computed data including among others simple spreadsheets
Changes bubble up through the dependency heirarchy
Cyclical dependencies will ping pong to eternity, unless a time windowed max calc counters is maintained wrt registers
Register id/address could have group component to allow large hierarchies to be formed, without overwelming the dependecy and dirty list(s)

column4: Multiple shared(/global) dirty lists, each representing a kind of a group
